ket forces and political reform that has led straight into Latin America's most serious problems. John Sheahan addresses three central concerns: the persistence of poverty in Latin American countries despite rising national incomes, the connection between economic troubles and political repression, and the relationships between Latin America and the rest of the world in trade and finance, as well as overall dependence. His comprehensive explanation of why many Latin Americans identify open political systems with frustration and economic breakdown will interest not only economists but also a broad range of other social scientists. This is "political economy" in the classical sense of the word, establishing a clear connection between the political and economic realities of Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aPolitical rightszLatin America. 0aPoorzLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAlliance for Progress.  aBosch, Juan.  aCarter administration.  aCatholic Church.  aChristian Democrats (Chile).  aDominican Republic.  aEcuador.  aEl Salvador.  aFrei, Eduardo.  aFrondizi, Arturo.  aGoulart, João.  aHaiti.  aHonduras.  aInter-American Foundation.  aJohnson administration.  aKennedy administration.  aLópez Portilló, José.  aNational Front (Colombia).  aPanama.  aReagan administration.  aSoviet Union.  aUnidad Popular.  aVelasco government.  aVenezuela.  aagriculture and rural labor.  aautonomy, national.  abalance of payments, foreign exchange.  abureaucratic-authoritarian regimes.  acapital flight.  achild and infant mortality.  adebt and external credit.  aeconomic growth.  aemployment, labor markets.  afood prices and supply.  aguerrilla movements.  ahuman rights.  aincomes policy.  aindustrialization